nnually improves fund returns by 40 bps per year relative to rebalancing qu=
arterly. We argue this is because sleepy rebalancing avoids the short-and m=
edium-term adverse selection associated with relatively quickly taking the =
other side of firms' primary and secondary market activity.=C2=A0</p></bloc=
